    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes! The Circle of Fifths has a very specific pattern for counting sharps and flats that will help you identify the key. When you see a key signature with three sharps, you can look at the circle to find where the sharps appear. Starting from C major (no sharps), moving clockwise one step gives G major (one sharp), the next step is D major (two sharps), and the third step is A major (three sharps). So, three sharps means the key is A major. The pattern is consistent: each step clockwise adds one sharp, and the key with three sharps is always A major. If you ever see three flats, you would move counter-clockwise from C major to F major (one flat), then Bb major (two flats), and finally Eb major (three flats).",
      "source": "target",
