      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely! The Circle of Fifths is a powerful tool for understanding chords and how songs move between sections. One of its most common uses is in chord progressions: because the circle lists keys in a sequence of fifths, you can often move between keys that are next to each other on the circle to create smooth harmonic transitions. For example, a progression like I–V–vi–IV (tonic–dominant–submediant–subtonic) in C major would be C (no sharps) → G (one sharp) → A (three sharps) → F (one flat). This is a very common pattern in pop and rock music because it keeps the harmony logical and ear-friendly. The circle also helps you see how related keys share similar chord qualities, making it easier to write or analyze music that moves fluidly from one key to another.",
